problem.markdown:
>>Permuting the examples of a dataset has an impact on the probability of the dataset \( P_D(S) \). Is this statement true or false? ||You only have one attempt for this question.||<<


( )True {{Because of the independent and identically distributed assumption, we have that \(P_D(S) = \prod_{i=1}^m P_D(x_i, y_i) \) which is invariant to any change of ordering. You should always shuffle a dataset in the iid framework.}}
(x) False {{Because of the independent and identically distributed assumption, we have that \(P_D(S) = \prod_{i=1}^m P_D(x_i, y_i) \) which is invariant to any change of ordering. You should always shuffle a dataset in the iid framework.}}

||Refer to the probability formula of a dataset in 1.2.2a Supervised Learning - Part I.||
